description: ServiceWiringBeanFactoryPostProcessor would be cleaner and more flexible if it didn't store references.  It only needs to block until all the services are created, and then as many additional slices or other contributions as needed could be added which just consume the services. Really, I suppose the method getApplicationContextCount() in SlicesPersonality is asking not for a count of contexts, but a count of the number of contexts that are contributing services.  If some personalities can guarantee never to publish services it is unnecessary to wait for them to initialize before the wiring begins.
summary: ServiceWiringBeanFactoryPostProcessor would be cleaner and more flexible if it didn't store references

description: SpringApplicationSlicePersonality probably shouldn't call ApplicationContext.start().  The Spring Framework context loaders do not call start() and in Spring 3.0 there is a LifecycleProcessor protocol for starting the lifecycles in the context with a default behaviour, but overridable.
